'''''Bishop Petros with Saint Peter the Apostle''''' ({{Lang-pl|Biskup Petros ze świętym Piotrem Apostołem}}) is a [[Nubia]]n Christian wall painting from the last quarter of the 10th century.{{Sfn|Mierzejewska|2016|loc="Opis"}}{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|pp=180–182}} Made with [[tempera]] on [[silt]] [[plaster]] using a [[Fresco-secco|''al secco'']] [[fresco]] technique, it depicts Petros, the bishop of [[Faras]] between 974 and 997. The anonymous work was discovered in the ruins of [[Faras Cathedral]], an important religious centre of Nubia, in modern [[Sudan]]. Rescued from flooding when [[Lake Nasser]] was created, since 1964 it is part of the Faras Gallery of the [[National Museum, Warsaw|National Museum in Warsaw]].{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|pp=180–182}}

The painting, which used to be part of a larger composition, representing King [[Georgios II of Makuria]] with the [[Virgin and Child]], was painted on the west wall of the chapel located in the southern [[nave]] of the cathedral.  The portrait of the bishop was placed to the right of the image of the king. The representation of the two highest hierarchs of the state along with their [[patron saints]] indicated the supernatural origin of the power of the nobles and symbolized the unity of the clerical and secular power.{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|p=182}}

The image was created in Petros' lifetime, which is suggested by the inscription in Greek accompanying the painting, wishing him "many years [of life]".{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|pp=180–182}} The painting is considered one of the most precious images of Nubian officials found in the Cathedral of Faras{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|pp=180–182}} and is also one of six best preserved portraits of bishops discovered there.{{sfn|Gołgowski|1967|p=176}}

== History ==
The painting, like most other pieces of {{Interlanguage link multi|Christian Nubian art|pl|3=Chrześcijańskie malarstwo nubijskie|lt=Nubian art}} in the {{Interlanguage link multi|Faras Gallery|pl|3=Galeria Faras im. Profesora Kazimierza Michałowskiego w Muzeum Narodowym w Warszawie}} of the [[National Museum, Warsaw|National Museum in Warsaw]], was recovered by Polish archaeologists during the so-called Nubian Campaign, an international effort led by [[UNESCO]] prior to construction of the [[Lake Nasser|Nasser Dam]]. The excavations, carried out between 1961 and 1964, discovered a religious complex in the town of Faras (ancient Pachoras), near modern Sudanese-Egyptian border. Well-preserved ruins of a large Christian cathedral from 7th to 14th centuries contained well-preserved wall religious paintings.{{Sfn|Sulikowska|2015|loc=¶ 1–12}}

Since the area was to be flooded by the waters of the artificial Lake Nasser, a team of Polish archaeologists led by [[Kazimierz Michałowski]] was allowed to recover the artifacts. A major part was then transported to the [[National Museum of Sudan]], where a team of Polish scientists led by [[Józef Gazy]] carried out {{Interlanguage link multi|Conservation and restoration of Faras wall paintings|pl|3=Konserwacja i restauracja malowideł ściennych z Faras|lt=their conservation}}. Some 40 per cent were transported to the National Museum of Warsaw, becoming the nucleus of the future Faras Gallery.{{Sfn|Sulikowska|2015|loc=¶ 1–12}}

The image itself was painted by an anonymous artist some time during bishop Petros' tenure, between 974 and 999 AD.{{Sfn|Michałowski|1974}} It represents the so-called yellow and red style, typical of a transitional period between the white style of 9th century and later multicolour style introduced in the 11th century and typical of all later wall paintings at Faras until its abandonment in the 14th century. Other images representative of the yellow and red style found at Faras represent King Georgios, a ''Virgin and Child'', ''Three Men in the Fiery Furnace'', as well as a Passion Cycle. The red and yellow style paintings are considered among the most interesting, both visually and for their theological message.{{Sfn|Michałowski|1974}}

== Description ==
[[File:Faras_-_Restoration_in_MNW-04.jpg|thumb|Work on conservation and restoration of the fresco in Warsaw's National Museum, 1964–1966]]

The dark-skinned bishop is depicted wearing his liturgical robes, complete with a narrow, white handkerchief (''[[encheiron]]'') wound around the index finger of his right palm. With it he points at a [[Gospel Book]] he holds in his other arm.{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|pp=180–182}}

Petros is dressed in a long white robe (''[[sticharion]]'') with vertical green stripes. His yellow ''[[phelonion]]'' (a type of [[chasuble]]), in the shape of an elongated ellipse, is adorned with a pattern of a red net, with precious stones sewn into the fabric. The edge of the chasuble is also adorned with a strip of fabric with green and red jewels. Bishop's ''[[epitrachelion]]'' is decorated with yellow wheels with a green circuit and red rectangles.{{sfn|Gołgowski|1967|p=178}} The ''[[omophorion]]'', one of symbols of episcopal dignity, is white with a pattern of circles and rectangles.{{sfn|Gołgowski|1967|pp=181–182}} The head of the bishop is wrapped in a turban characteristic of the [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Church]] hierarchs, which could suggest that Petros was a [[Monophysitism|monophysite]].{{sfn|Gołgowski|1967|pp=186–188}}

Behind the bishop stands Saint [[Saint Peter|Peter the Apostle]], dressed in a white crown signifying martyrdom. The saint has both hands on the shoulders of the bishop.{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|pp=180–182}} This pose, common in Nubian painting of the epoch, signifies the fact that the saint protects and supports the bishop,{{sfn|Martens-Czarnecka|2006|p=35}} but also points at the supernatural character of bishop's power.{{sfn|Mierzejewska|2014|pp=180–182}}

Around the head of Saint Peter there is a black inscription in Greek: SAINT PETER THE APOSTLE MARTYR OF THE CROSS ABBA PETROS BISHOP AND METROPOLITAN OF PACHORAS [may he live] MANY YEARS.{{Sfn|Mierzejewska|2016|loc="Opis"}}

