{{Infobox person | name = Catarina Lobo Portas | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = Catarina de Sousa Lobo Martins Portas | birth_date = 1969 | birth_place = Lisbon | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) --> | death_place = | nationality = Portuguese | other_names = | occupation = Journalist and businesswoman | parents = {{unbulleted list|Nuno Portas|Margarida Lobo}} }}
'''Catarina de Sousa Lobo Martins Portas''' ([[Lisbon]], 1969) is a [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] [[journalist]] and [[businesswoman]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.avidaportuguesa.com/sobre/fundadora_3 |title=Biography |publisher=Avidaportuguesa.com |access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>
== Biography == She is the daughter of the architect Nuno Portas and of his second wife, Margarida Maria Gomes de Sousa Lobo and half sister of the politicians [[Miguel Portas]] and [[Paulo Portas]]. Catarina became a [[journalist]] in 1988 and worked on the radio (''Correio da Manhã Rádio'' and ''Rádio Comercial'') and on television, firstly in [[Rádio e Televisão de Portugal|RTP]] (''Onda Curta'', ''Falatório'', ''Raios e Coriscos'' and ''Frou Frou''), and then in [[Sociedade Independente de Comunicação|SIC]]. Since 2004, she became a businesswoman, with the inauguration of the ''A Vida Portuguesa'' stores, dedicated to the reselling of [[vintage]] [[Portugal|Portuguese]] brands. In December 2009, she was nominated by the [[Monocle]] magazine as one of the twenty worldwide names that deserve "a bigger stage".
